      context: "Acts 2:42-47 is a compressed portrait of the Jerusalem church in its earliest weeks: four interlocking practices that defined its life — doctrine (the apostles' teaching), fellowship (koinonia), breaking of bread (shared meals, likely including the Lord's Supper), and prayers. The Greek word for fellowship — koinonia — is not a synonym for socialising. It means participation in a shared thing, a common life. These believers had their possessions in common (v.44), sold what they had and distributed to those in need (v.45), met daily in the Temple courts and in homes (v.46), and ate together with joy and generosity of heart. The result was not social management but organic growth: 'the Lord added to the church daily such as should be saved' (v.47). The church did not primarily grow through evangelistic campaigns — it grew because the community was so visibly transformed that outsiders were drawn in. Hebrews 10:24-25 addresses this community dimension directly: 'Let us consider one another to provoke unto love and to good works: Not forsaking the assembling of ourselves together, as the manner of some is; but exhorting one another: and so much the more, as ye see the day approaching.' The Greek word for 'consider' (katanoeo) means to observe carefully, to study attentively — suggesting that genuine Christian community requires intentional attention to each other's spiritual and practical needs, not passive co-existence. The phrase 'provoke unto love' is striking: the Greek is paroxusmos — to stimulate, to stir up (the same word used for a sharp disagreement in Acts 15:39). The early Christians were to sharpen each other into love and good works, not settle into comfortable religious routine.",
