    memoryVerse: "Now there are diversities of gifts, but the same Spirit. And there are differences of administrations, but the same Lord. And there are diversities of operations, but it is the same God which worketh all in all. — 1 Corinthians 12:4-6",
    closingPrayer: "Holy Spirit — You are the Giver of every gift. You distribute to each one as You will, for the benefit of all. Forgive me for comparing my gifts to others', for envying the visible gifts and despising the quiet ones, for burying what You gave me rather than deploying it. Teach me what You have put in me that is for others. Open my eyes to see the body I belong to — every member necessary, every contribution significant, every gift an expression of Your grace. Use me for the building up of Your church. Use me for the advance of Your gospel. And let everything I do be done in the love without which all gifts are noise. Amen.",

    leaderNote: "Week 44 has strong practical potential. Consider doing a simple gifts-reflection activity: give students the Romans 12 list and ask them to circle the top 2-3 that resonate most, then share in pairs. This is non-threatening and surprisingly illuminating. The George Müller story illustrates a quiet, non-spectacular gift used with extraordinary faithfulness — and counters the Corinthian tendency (alive in every youth group) to overvalue public speaking gifts. The most important pastoral point: every student has a gift. Every. The session should end with students at least beginning to name what theirs might be. Follow up with leadership: create a specific serving opportunity between now and Week 52 for each student to use a gift they named.",
